illiam L. |last=North |title=Medieval Germany: An Encyclopedia |editor-first=John M. |editor-last=Jeep  |publisher=Garland Publishing Inc. |year=2001 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=C.W. |last=Previt\u00e9-Orton |title=The Early History of the House of Savoy |url=https://archive.org/details/earlyhistoryofh00prev |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1912 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.dmgh.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb00000448_00011.html?zoom=0.75&leftTab=toc&sortIndex=030:040:0004:010:00:00 |title= Conrad II, Diplomata [Urkunden] |publisher= Monumenta Germaniae Historica (dMGH)  | |ref=harv | author= | accessdate= January 29, 2020 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[Salian dynasty]] ||c 990||1039}}\n{{S-reg|}}\n|-\n{{S-vac|rows=3|last=[[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry the Saint]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of German Kings and Emperors|King of Germany]]|years=1024\u20131039|regent1=[[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry III]]|years1=1028\u20131039}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry the Black]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Holy Roman Emperor]]|years=1027\u20131039}}\n{{S-vac|rows=3|next=[[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry the Black]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[King of Italy]]|years=1027\u20131039|}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Rudolph III of Burgundy|Rudolph the Pious]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[King of Burgundy]]|years=1032\u20131039|regent1=[[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry the Black]]|years1=1028\u20131039}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Holy Roman Emperors}}\n{{German monarchs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conrad Ii, Holy Roman Emperor}}\n[[Category:990 births]]\n[[Category:1039 deaths]]\n[[Category:11th-century Holy Roman Emperors]]\n[[Category:Salian dynasty]]\n[[Category:German kings of Burgundy]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Carinthia]]\n[[Category:Burials at Speyer Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Burials at St. Martin's Cathedral, Utrecht]]\n[[Category:People from Speyer]]\n", "name_user": "Wikirictor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnrest in Italy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conrad_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor"}
{"title_page": "Benny Andersen", "text_new": "{{about|the Danish poet|the sailor|Benny F. Andersen}}\n{{Distinguish|Benny Andersson}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = benny-andersen DSC03905.jpg\n| caption     = Benny Andersen at the 2009 Danish book fair\n| name        = Benny Andersen\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1929|11|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Vangede]], Denmark\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2018|8|16|1929|11|7|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Sorgenfri]], Denmark\n| occupation  = Writer\n| nationality = Danish\n| period      = 1960\u20132018\n| genre       = \n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n'''Benny Andersen''' (7 November 1929 &ndash; 16 August 2018)<ref name=bt>[https://www.bt.dk/samfund/benny-andersen-er-doed Benny Andersen er d\u00f8d] ''[[BT (tabloid)|BT]]'' 17 August 2018</ref> was a Danish poet, author, songwriter, composer and pianist. He is often remembered for his collaboration with the singer [[Povl Dissing]]; together they released an album with Andersen's poems from the collection ''Svantes viser''. This album and Andersen's book \"''Svantes viser''\" (Svante's Songs) from 1972 were included by the Danish Ministry of Culture in the [[Danish Culture Canon]] in 2006, in the category \"Popular music\".<ref>[http://www.denstoredanske.dk/Kunst_og_kultur/Litteratur/Genrebegreber/Kulturkanon Denstoredanske.dk] Kulturkanon</ref><ref>[http://www.sydsvenskan.se/kultur--nojen/hela-den-danska-kulturkanonen/ Hela den danska Kulturkanonen] (in Swedish) [[Sydsvenskan]], retrieved January 20, 2013</ref> Andersen's \"''Samlede digte''\" (Collected poems) have sold more than 100,000 copies in Denmark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.curbstone.org/authdetail.cfm?AuthID=107|title=Benny Andersen|accessdate=22 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn Denmark, Benny Andersen was also a well-known author of children's literature and in 1971, he was awarded the [[Ministry of Culture's children book prize (Denmark)|Ministry of Culture's children book prize (\"''Kulturministeriets B\u00f8rnebogspris''\")]].<ref>[http://www.kunststyrelsen.dk/db/files/modtagere_boernebog.pdf Kunststyrelsen.dk] List of recipients of the Kulturministeriets B\u00f8rnebogspris</ref> In the 1980s, his books about the fantastical creature Sn\u00f8vsen, became widely popular and later inspired two films in the early 90s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saxo.com/dk/alle-historierne-om-snoevsen_benny-andersen_indbundet_9788702165333|title=Alle historierne om sn\u00f8vsen|publisher=Saxo|language=Danish|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAndersen became a member of the [[Danish Academy]] (Det Danske Akademi) in 1972.\n\nHis wife, the jurist Elisabeth Ehmer, reported that Benny Andersen died in the family home in [[Sorgenfri]], north of [[Copenhagen]], on 16 August 2018.<ref name=bt/>\n\n== Selected bibliography ==\nSome of Benny Andersen's notable poem collections, includes:\n* ''Den musikalske \u00e5l'', 1960\n* ''Kamera med k\u00f8kkenadgang'', 1962\n* ''Nikke Nikke Nambo og andre danske b\u00f8rnerim og remser, 1963\n* ''Den indre bowlerhat'', 1964\n* ''Portr\u00e6tgalleri'', 1966\n* ''Det sidste \u00f8h og andre digte'', 1969\n* ''Her i reservatet'', 1971\n* ''Svantes viser'', Borgen, 1972\n* ''Personlige papirer'', 1974\n* ''Under begge \u00f8jne'', 1978\n* ''Himmelspr\u00e6t (eller kunsten at komme til verden)'', 1979\n* ''Tiden og storken'', 1985\n* ''H.C. Andersens land'', 1985\n* ''Chagall og skorpiondans'', 1991\n* ''Denne kommen og g\u00e5en'', 1993\n* ''Mit liv som indvandrer'', 1993\n* ''Verdensborger i Danmark'', 1995\n* ''Verden udenfor syltet\u00f8jsglasset'', 1996\n* ''Sj\u00e6len marineret'', 2001\n* ''Svantes lykkelige dag'', 2003\n* ''Spredte digte'', 2005\n* ''Den Vilde Ungdom'', 2005\n* ''Kram'', 2009\n* ''Den n\u00f8gne mand'', 2010\n\nA few of his short stories:\n* ''Bukserne'', 1963\n* ''Et lykkeligt menneske'', 1968\n* ''Samlede noveller'', 2003\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071212163004/http://bibliografi.dk/content.php?page=author&value=10123 Biography from biografi.dk](in Danish).\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081021163012/http://www.litteratursiden.dk/sw70592.asp Benny Andersen - Biography from ''Litteratur.dk''] (in Danish).\n*[http://www.litteraturpriser.dk/d.asp?type=aut&side=ABennyAndersen Benny Andersen - Literature prizes] (in Danish).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Benny Andersen}}\n*[http://www.the-discographer.dk/benny-andersen.pdf The-discographer.dk, Benny Andersen's bibliography with photos]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andersen, Benny}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish male poets]]\n[[Category:Danish composers]]\n[[Category:Male composers]]\n[[Category:Danish pianists]]\n[[Category:Danish male short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:Male pianists]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Danish poet|the sailor|Benny F. Andersen}}\n{{Distinguish|Benny Andersson}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = benny-andersen DSC03905.jpg\n| caption     = Benny Andersen at the 2009 Danish book fair\n| name        = Benny Andersen\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1929|11|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Vangede]], Denmark\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2018|8|16|1929|11|7|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Sorgenfri]], Denmark\n| occupation  = Writer\n| nationality = Danish\n| period      = 1960\u20132018\n| genre       = \n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n'''Benny Andersen''' (7 November 1929 &ndash; 16 August 2018)<ref name=bt>[https://www.bt.dk/samfund/benny-andersen-er-doed Benny Andersen er d\u00f8d] ''[[BT (tabloid)|BT]]'' 17 August 2018</ref> was a Danish poet, author, songwriter, composer and pianist. He is often remembered for his collaboration with the singer [[Povl Dissing]]; together they released an album with Andersen's poems from the collection ''Svantes viser''. This album and Andersen's book \"''Svantes viser''\" (Svante's Songs) from 1972 were included by the Danish Ministry of Culture in the [[Danish Culture Canon]] in 2006, in the category \"Popular music\".<ref>[http://www.denstoredanske.dk/Kunst_og_kultur/Litteratur/Genrebegreber/Kulturkanon Denstoredanske.dk] Kulturkanon</ref><ref>[http://www.sydsvenskan.se/kultur--nojen/hela-den-danska-kulturkanonen/ Hela den danska Kulturkanonen] (in Swedish) [[Sydsvenskan]], retrieved January 20, 2013</ref> Andersen's \"''Samlede digte''\" (Collected poems) have sold more than 100,000 copies in Denmark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.curbstone.org/authdetail.cfm?AuthID=107|title=Benny Andersen|accessdate=22 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn Denmark, Benny Andersen was also a well-known author of children's literature and in 1971, he was awarded the [[Ministry of Culture's children book prize (Denmark)|Ministry of Culture's children book prize (\"''Kulturministeriets B\u00f8rnebogspris''\")]].<ref>[http://www.kunststyrelsen.dk/db/files/modtagere_boernebog.pdf Kunststyrelsen.dk] List of recipients of the Kulturministeriets B\u00f8rnebogspris</ref> In the 1980s, his books about the fantastical creature Sn\u00f8vsen, became widely popular and later inspired two films in the early 90s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saxo.com/dk/alle-historierne-om-snoevsen_benny-andersen_indbundet_9788702165333|title=Alle historierne om sn\u00f8vsen|publisher=Saxo|language=Danish|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAndersen became a member of the [[Danish Academy]] (Det Danske Akademi) in 1972.\n\nHis wife, the jurist Elisabeth Ehmer, reported that Benny Andersen died in the family home in [[Sorgenfri]], north of [[Copenhagen]], on 16 August 2018.<ref name=bt/>\n\n== Selected bibliography ==\nSome of Benny Andersen's notable poem collections, includes:\n* ''Den musikalske \u00e5l'', 1960\n* ''Kamera med k\u00f8kkenadgang'', 1962\n* ''Nikke Nikke Nambo og andre danske b\u00f8rnerim og remser, 1963\n* ''Den indre bowlerhat'', 1964\n* ''Portr\u00e6tgalleri'', 1966\n* ''Det sidste \u00f8h og andre digte'', 1969\n* ''Her i reservatet'', 1971\n* ''Svantes viser'', Borgen, 1972\n* ''Personlige papirer'', 1974\n* ''Under begge \u00f8jne'', 1978\n* ''Himmelspr\u00e6t (eller kunsten at komme til verden)'', 1979\n* ''Tiden og storken'', 1985\n* ''H.C. Andersens land'', 1985\n* ''Chagall og skorpiondans'', 1991\n* ''Denne kommen og g\u00e5en'', 1993\n* ''Mit liv som indvandrer'', 1993\n* ''Verdensborger i Danmark'', 1995\n* ''Verden udenfor syltet\u00f8jsglasset'', 1996\n* ''Sj\u00e6len marineret'', 2001\n* ''Svantes lykkelige dag'', 2003\n* ''Spredte digte'', 2005\n* ''Den Vilde Ungdom'', 2005\n* ''Kram'', 2009\n* ''Den n\u00f8gne mand'', 2010\n\nA few of his short stories:\n* ''Bukserne'', 1963\n* ''Et lykkeligt menneske'', 1968\n* ''Samlede noveller'', 2003\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071212163004/http://bibliografi.dk/content.php?page=author&value=10123 Biography from biografi.dk](in Danish).\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081021163012/http://www.litteratursiden.dk/sw70592.asp Benny Andersen - Biography from ''Litteratur.dk''] (in Danish).\n*[http://www.litteraturpriser.dk/d.asp?type=aut&side=ABennyAndersen Benny Andersen - Literature prizes] (in Danish).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Benny Andersen}}\n*[http://www.the-discographer.dk/benny-andersen.pdf The-discographer.dk, Benny Andersen's bibliography with photos]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andersen, Benny}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish male poets]]\n[[Category:Danish composers]]\n[[Category:Male composers]]\n[[Category:Danish pianists]]\n[[Category:Danish male short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Male pianists]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benny_Andersen"}
{"title_page": "Klaus Rifbjerg", "text_new": "[[File:Klaus-rifbjerg DSC03877.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Klaus Rifbjerg in 2009]]\n'''Klaus Rifbjerg''' (15 December 1931 \u2013 4 April 2015) was a Danish writer. He authored more than 170 novels, books and essays.<ref>Afterbeat. En samtale med Klaus Rifbjerg, Henrik Juul Jensen, 1996, {{ISBN|87-16-14257-8}}</ref> In 1965 he co-produced the film ''[[4x4 (1965 film)|4x4]]'' which was entered into the [[4th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1965\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |title=4th Moscow International Film Festival (1965) |accessdate=2012-12-02 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116145645/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |archivedate=2013-01-16 }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nRifbjerg was born in [[Copenhagen]] and grew up on the island of [[Amager]], which is part of the city, the child of two teachers. Later he studied English and literature, in Copenhagen and for a year in the US at [[Princeton University]].\n\nHis breakthrough was in 1958 with the novel ''Den kroniske Uskyld''. It was made into a film in 1985, directed by Edward Fleming. From that time on he published more than 100 novels as well as poetry and short story collections, plays, TV and radio plays, film scripts, children's books and diaries. Rifbjerg is also known for having been a journalist and critic. Along with [[Villy S\u00f8rensen]], he was editor of the publication ''[[Vindrosen]]'', and from 1984 to 1991 he was the literary director of [[Gyldendal (Denmark)|Gyldendal]].\n\nAmong other honors, he was awarded the [[Swedish Academy Nordic Prize]] (1999), known as the 'little Nobel'{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}; [[The Nordic Council's Literature Prize]] (1970), the [[Rungstedlund Award]] (2009) and the [[Grand Prize of the Danish Academy|grand prize]] of the [[Danish Academy]] (1966).\n\nRifbjerg has been seen as the first true modernist author in Danish, as he became increasingly more experimental though the 1960s, culminating with ''[[Anna, I, Anna|Anna (jeg) Anna]]''. Many of his works from 1970 and some 25 years on are seen as being looser in scope and composition, often humorous or sarcastic, often leaving the protagonist chaotically alone with his or her existential and psychological hangups, subtly exemplifying modernism as the breakdown of the normality of the bourgeoisie. A principal theme is the portrayal of children and their difficulties establishing their own identity. Rifbjerg's works from the 2000s opened a new line of inspiration: historic events.\n\nOn 4 April 2015 Rifbjerg died in Copenhagen after a long illness, aged 83.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.information.dk/telegram/529260|title=Klaus Rifbjerg skrev over 150 titler - nu er han d\u00f8d|publisher=Information.dk|accessdate=April 5, 2015|language=da}}</ref><ref name=\"dead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dr.dk/Nyheder/Indland/2015/04/05/084413.htm |title=Forfatteren Klaus Rifbjerg er d\u00f8d |language=Danish |trans-title=The author Klaus Rifbjerg is dead |author=Danmarks Radio |authorlink=DR (broadcaster) |work=dr.dk |date=2015-04-05 |accessdate=2015-04-05 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.thelocal.dk/20150407/major-danish-author-passes-away Rifbjerg remembered for writing style, legacy]</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Under vejr med mig selv'' (1956)\n* ''Efterkrig'' (1957)\n* ''Den kroniske uskyld'' (1958)\n* ''Konfrontation'' (1960)\n* ''Og andre historier'' (1964)\n* ''Operaelskeren'' (1966)\n* ''Lonni og Karl'' (1968)\n* ''[[Anna, I, Anna|Anna (jeg) Anna]]'' (1969)\n* ''Lena J\u00f8rgensen Klintevej 4 2650 Hvidovre'' (1971)\n* ''Tak for turen'' (1975)\n* ''De hellige aber'' (1981); English translation ''[[Witness to the Future]]'' by [[Steven T. Murray]] (1987)\n* ''Falsk for\u00e5r'' (1984)\n* ''[[Tukuma (film)|Tukuma]]'' (1984)\n* ''Krigen'' (1991); English translation ''War'' by [[Steven T. Murray]] & [[Tiina Nunnally]] (1995)\n* ''Nansen og Johansen'' (2002)\n* ''Knast\u00f8rre digte/Strohtrockene Gedichte'' (2009); German translation by Lutz Volke [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lutz_Volke], edited by [[Paul Alfred Kleinert]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071212174449/http://bibliografi.dk/content.php?page=author&value=12514 Bibliografi profile]\n*[http://www.litteraturpriser.dk/aut/rk.htm#RKlausRifbjerg Litteraturpriser biography]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719122403/http://agent.dril.dk/agent/style/grundskole_kanon/default.aspx?play26906 Danmarks Radio clips]\n*{{IMDb name|0726440}}\n\n{{The Nordic Council's Literature Prize}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rifbjerg, Klaus}}\n[[Category:Danish male poets]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Nordic Council Literature Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Prize of the Danish Academy]]\n[[Category:Danish male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:Danish male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:Critics employed by Politiken]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Klaus-rifbjerg DSC03877.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Klaus Rifbjerg in 2009]]\n'''Klaus Rifbjerg''' (15 December 1931 \u2013 4 April 2015) was a Danish writer. He authored more than 170 novels, books and essays.<ref>Afterbeat. En samtale med Klaus Rifbjerg, Henrik Juul Jensen, 1996, {{ISBN|87-16-14257-8}}</ref> In 1965 he co-produced the film ''[[4x4 (1965 film)|4x4]]'' which was entered into the [[4th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1965\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |title=4th Moscow International Film Festival (1965) |accessdate=2012-12-02 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116145645/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |archivedate=2013-01-16 }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nRifbjerg was born in [[Copenhagen]] and grew up on the island of [[Amager]], which is part of the city, the child of two teachers. Later he studied English and literature, in Copenhagen and for a year in the US at [[Princeton University]].\n\nHis breakthrough was in 1958 with the novel ''Den kroniske Uskyld''. It was made into a film in 1985, directed by Edward Fleming. From that time on he published more than 100 novels as well as poetry and short story collections, plays, TV and radio plays, film scripts, children's books and diaries. Rifbjerg is also known for having been a journalist and critic. Along with [[Villy S\u00f8rensen]], he was editor of the publication ''[[Vindrosen]]'', and from 1984 to 1991 he was the literary director of [[Gyldendal (Denmark)|Gyldendal]].\n\nAmong other honors, he was awarded the [[Swedish Academy Nordic Prize]] (1999), known as the 'little Nobel'{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}; [[The Nordic Council's Literature Prize]] (1970), the [[Rungstedlund Award]] (2009) and the [[Grand Prize of the Danish Academy|grand prize]] of the [[Danish Academy]] (1966).\n\nRifbjerg has been seen as the first true modernist author in Danish, as he became increasingly more experimental though the 1960s, culminating with ''[[Anna, I, Anna|Anna (jeg) Anna]]''. Many of his works from 1970 and some 25 years on are seen as being looser in scope and composition, often humorous or sarcastic, often leaving the protagonist chaotically alone with his or her existential and psychological hangups, subtly exemplifying modernism as the breakdown of the normality of the bourgeoisie. A principal theme is the portrayal of children and their difficulties establishing their own identity. Rifbjerg's works from the 2000s opened a new line of inspiration: historic events.\n\nOn 4 April 2015 Rifbjerg died in Copenhagen after a long illness, aged 83.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.information.dk/telegram/529260|title=Klaus Rifbjerg skrev over 150 titler - nu er han d\u00f8d|publisher=Information.dk|accessdate=April 5, 2015|language=da}}</ref><ref name=\"dead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dr.dk/Nyheder/Indland/2015/04/05/084413.htm |title=Forfatteren Klaus Rifbjerg er d\u00f8d |language=Danish |trans-title=The author Klaus Rifbjerg is dead |author=Danmarks Radio |authorlink=DR (broadcaster) |work=dr.dk |date=2015-04-05 |accessdate=2015-04-05 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.thelocal.dk/20150407/major-danish-author-passes-away Rifbjerg remembered for writing style, legacy]</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Under vejr med mig selv'' (1956)\n* ''Efterkrig'' (1957)\n* ''Den kroniske uskyld'' (1958)\n* ''Konfrontation'' (1960)\n* ''Og andre historier'' (1964)\n* ''Operaelskeren'' (1966)\n* ''Lonni og Karl'' (1968)\n* ''[[Anna, I, Anna|Anna (jeg) Anna]]'' (1969)\n* ''Lena J\u00f8rgensen Klintevej 4 2650 Hvidovre'' (1971)\n* ''Tak for turen'' (1975)\n* ''De hellige aber'' (1981); English translation ''[[Witness to the Future]]'' by [[Steven T. Murray]] (1987)\n* ''Falsk for\u00e5r'' (1984)\n* ''[[Tukuma (film)|Tukuma]]'' (1984)\n* ''Krigen'' (1991); English translation ''War'' by [[Steven T. Murray]] & [[Tiina Nunnally]] (1995)\n* ''Nansen og Johansen'' (2002)\n* ''Knast\u00f8rre digte/Strohtrockene Gedichte'' (2009); German translation by Lutz Volke [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lutz_Volke], edited by [[Paul Alfred Kleinert]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071212174449/http://bibliografi.dk/content.php?page=author&value=12514 Bibliografi profile]\n*[http://www.litteraturpriser.dk/aut/rk.htm#RKlausRifbjerg Litteraturpriser biography]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719122403/http://agent.dril.dk/agent/style/grundskole_kanon/default.aspx?play26906 Danmarks Radio clips]\n*{{IMDb name|0726440}}\n\n{{The Nordic Council's Literature Prize}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rifbjerg, Klaus}}\n[[Category:Danish male poets]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Nordic Council Literature Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Grand Prize of the Danish Academy]]\n[[Category:Danish male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:Danish male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Critics employed by Politiken]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klaus_Rifbjerg"}
